<div class="container-fluid main-container">




<div id="header">



<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Statistical Analysis with R Workshop</h1>
<h4 class="author">Albina Gibadullina and Maria Laricheva</h4>
<h4 class="date">November 26, 2021</h4>

</div>


<div id="installing-and-loading-r-packages" class="section level1">
<h1>Installing and loading R packages</h1>
<p>This workshop uses the following R packages:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>psych</em>, a statistical analysis package</li>
<li><em>rstatix</em>, a statistical analysis package</li>
<li><em>dplyr</em>, a data manipulation package</li>
<li><em>DT</em>, a package for creating interactive tables</li>
<li><em>ggplot2</em>, a data visualization package</li>
<li><em>GGally</em>, a data visualization package (extension of ggplot2)</li>
<li><em>table1</em>, a package for creating summary tables</li>
<li><em>gtsummary</em>, a package for creating summary tables</li>
<li><em>flextable</em>, a package for tabular reporting</li>
<li><em>modelsummary</em>, a package creating summary tables and plots</li>
<li><em>lmtest</em>, a package for linear regression</li>
<li><em>stargazer</em>, a package for exporting regression tables</li>
<li><em>car</em>, a package for regression analysis</li>
<li><em>RColorBrewer</em>, a color palette package</li>
<li><em>report</em>, a package for reporting statistical results</li>
<li><em>sjPlot</em>, a package for regression analysis tables and plots</li>
</ul>
<p>Check whether required packages are already installed, and install any that are missing</p>
<pre class="r"><code>list.of.packages &lt;- c(&quot;psych&quot;, &quot;rstatix&quot;,&quot;dplyr&quot;,&quot;DT&quot;,&quot;ggplot2&quot;,&quot;GGally&quot;,&quot;table1&quot;,&quot;gtsummary&quot;,&quot;flextable&quot;,&quot;modelsummary&quot;,&quot;lmtest&quot;,&quot;stargazer&quot;,&quot;car&quot;,&quot;RColorBrewer&quot;,&quot;remotes&quot;,&quot;report&quot;,&quot;sjPlot&quot;)
new.packages &lt;- list.of.packages[!(list.of.packages %in% installed.packages()[,&quot;Package&quot;])]
if(length(new.packages)) install.packages(new.packages)</code></pre>
<p>Load packages into your current session</p>
<pre class="r"><code>suppressPackageStartupMessages({
library(psych)
library(rstatix)
library(dplyr)
library(DT)
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)
library(table1)
library(gtsummary)
library(flextable)
library(modelsummary)  
library(lmtest)
library(stargazer)
library(car)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(report)
library(sjPlot)})</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="changing-default-theme-for-visualizations" class="section level1">
<h1>Changing default theme for visualizations</h1>
<p>Changing the default theme to theme_light</p>
<p>Suppress error messages</p>
</div>
<div id="uploading-data" class="section level1">
<h1>Uploading data</h1>
<p>Creating a data frame <code>scores</code> using an in-built dataset <code>sat.act</code> from the <code>psych</code> package</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores &lt;- sat.act</code></pre>
<p>Importing data from a .csv file (located in your working directory)</p>
<pre class="r"><code># scores &lt;- read.csv(&quot;sat.act.csv&quot;) # does not work in this case as you don&#39;t have a .csv file</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="describing-data-structure" class="section level1">
<h1>Describing data structure</h1>
<p>See the first six rows of the data frame</p>
<pre class="r"><code>head(scores) </code></pre>
<pre><code>##       gender education age ACT SATV SATQ
## 29442      2         3  19  24  500  500
## 29457      2         3  23  35  600  500
## 29498      2         3  20  21  480  470
## 29503      1         4  27  26  550  520
## 29504      1         2  33  31  600  550
## 29518      1         5  26  28  640  640</code></pre>
<p>Get dimension for your dataset</p>
<pre class="r"><code>dim(scores) # Get number of rows (observations) and number of columns (variables)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 700   6</code></pre>
<p>Check data structure</p>
<pre class="r"><code>str(scores)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## &#39;data.frame&#39;:    700 obs. of  6 variables:
##  $ gender   : int  2 2 2 1 1 1 2 1 2 2 ...
##  $ education: int  3 3 3 4 2 5 5 3 4 5 ...
##  $ age      : int  19 23 20 27 33 26 30 19 23 40 ...
##  $ ACT      : int  24 35 21 26 31 28 36 22 22 35 ...

<div id="data-manipulation" class="section level1">
<h1>Data manipulation</h1>
<div id="changing-format-of-variables" class="section level2">
<h2>Changing format of variables</h2>
<p>Check current data format of the <code>gender</code> variable</p>
<pre class="r"><code>class(scores$gender)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;integer&quot;</code></pre>
<p>Change the format of <code>gender</code> from integer (quantitative) to factor (categorical)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores$gender &lt;- as.factor(scores$gender)</code></pre>
<p>Check whether <code>gender</code> has factor format</p>
<pre class="r"><code>is.factor(scores$gender)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="exercise-1" class="section level2">
<h2>Exercise 1</h2>
<ul>
<li>Using <code>class</code> command, check the current format of <code>education</code></li>
<li>Using <code>as.factor</code> command, change <code>education</code> to factor.</li>
<li>Using <code>is.factor</code> command, check if <code>education</code> is defined as factor.</li>
</ul>
<p>Check current data format of the <code>education</code> variable</p>
<pre class="r"><code>class(scores$education)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;integer&quot;</code></pre>
<p>Change the format of <code>education</code> from integer (quantitative) to factor (categorical)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores$education &lt;- as.factor(scores$education)</code></pre>
<p>Check whether <code>education</code> has factor format</p>
<pre class="r"><code>is.factor(scores$education)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="transforming-values-of-categorical-variables" class="section level2">
<h2>Transforming values of categorical variables</h2>
<div id="gender" class="section level3">
<h3>Gender</h3>
<p><code>Gender</code> is now factor but it is still coded as 1 (men) and 2 (women) - it would be helpful for later analysis to change 1 to men and 2 to women</p>
<p>Replacing values</p>
<pre class="r"><code># Step 1: Change the data format to character
scores$gender &lt;- as.character(scores$gender)

# Step 2: Replace &quot;1&quot; with &quot;men&quot; and &quot;2&quot; with &quot;women&quot;
scores$gender[scores$gender==&quot;1&quot;] &lt;- &quot;Men&quot;
scores$gender[scores$gender==&quot;2&quot;] &lt;- &quot;Women&quot;

# Step 3: Change the data format back to factor
scores$gender &lt;- as.factor(scores$gender)

# Step 4: Check levels for `gender`
levels(scores$gender)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] &quot;Men&quot;   &quot;Women&quot;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

                                                    &quot;{median} ({min}, {max})&quot;), 
                               all_categorical() ~ &quot;{n} ({p}%)&quot;),
              digits = all_continuous() ~ 1) %&gt;% 
  add_p()

<div id="inferential-statistics" class="section level1">
<h1>Inferential Statistics</h1>
<p>You should select statistical tests based on your hypothesis and the data type of your variable(s)</p>
<ul>
<li>One sample t-test<br />
</li>
<li>Chi-square goodness of fit test</li>
<li>Two sample t-test<br />
</li>
<li>One-way ANOVA</li>
<li>Two-way ANOVA</li>
<li>Chi-square test of independence</li>
<li>Simple linear regression</li>
<li>Multiple linear regression<br />
</li>
<li>Simple logistic regression<br />
</li>
<li>Multiple logistic regression</li>
</ul>
<div id="one-sample-t-test" class="section level2">
<h2>One sample t-test</h2>
<p>It is used to see whether the hypothesized value of the population mean matches actual value.</p>
<p>Question: Is the average ACT score for all participants 27?</p>
<p>Visualize the distribution of ACT scores using a histogram with a normal distribution curve and a line for mean</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;%
  ggplot(aes(x = ACT)) + 
    geom_histogram(aes(y = stat(density)), binwidth = 2, 
                   color = &quot;black&quot;, fill = &quot;lightblue&quot;) +
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(scores$ACT), 
                                           sd = sd(scores$ACT)), size = 1) +
    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(ACT)), color = &quot;red&quot;) +
    labs(title = &quot;Histogram of ACT scores with a Normal Curve&quot;, 
         x = &quot;ACT score&quot;, y = &quot;Percent of observations&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run a one sample t-test</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m1 &lt;- t.test(scores$ACT, mu = 27,
       alternative = c(&quot;two.sided&quot;),
       conf.level = 0.95)
m1</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  scores$ACT
## t = 8.4862, df = 699, p-value &lt; 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 27
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  28.18920 28.90509
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  28.54714</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>report(m1)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Effect sizes were labelled following Cohen&#39;s (1988) recommendations.
## 
## The One Sample t-test testing the difference between scores$ACT (mean = 28.55) and mu = 27 suggests that the effect is positive, statistically significant, and small (difference = 1.55, 95% CI [28.19, 28.91], t(699) = 8.49, p &lt; .001; Cohen&#39;s d = 0.32, 95% CI [0.24, 0.40])</code></pre>
<p>t(df=699) = 8.4862, p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null) -&gt; The average ACT score is not 27.</p>
</div>
<div id="chi-square-goodness-of-fit" class="section level2">
<h2>Chi-square goodness of fit</h2>
<p>It is used to see whether the actual distribution (from a sample) of a categorical variable matches the expected distribution.</p>
<p>Question: Is gender distribution 50%-50% in this data set?</p>
<p>Make a relative bar-chart showing counts of observations by gender</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = gender, x = gender)) + 
    geom_bar(aes(y = stat(count)/sum(count))) +
    geom_text(aes(label = round(stat(count)/sum(count),2), y = stat(count)/sum(count)), 
              stat = &quot;count&quot;, position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 5) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;) +
    labs(title = &quot;Share of observations by gender&quot;,
         x = &quot;Gender&quot;, y = &quot;Percent of observations&quot;, fill = &quot;Gender&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run a Chi-square goodness of fit test</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m2 &lt;- chisq.test(table(scores$gender), p = c(0.5,0.5))
m2</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  table(scores$gender)
## X-squared = 60.623, df = 1, p-value = 6.913e-15</code></pre>
<p>X-squared(df=1) = 60.623, p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null) -&gt; The gender distribution is not 50%-50%.</p>
</div>
<div id="two-sample-t-test" class="section level2">
<h2>Two-sample t-test</h2>
<p>It is used to see whether there are group differences in population means between two groups.</p>
<p>Question: Do men and women have different average SAT verbal scores?</p>
<p>Use box plots to compare distributions of one quantitative variable across multiple categories</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;%
  ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = SATV, fill = gender)) +
    geom_boxplot(outlier.size = 1) +
    stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = &quot;point&quot;, shape = 5, size = 4) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;) +
    labs(title = &quot;Boxplots of SAT Verbal scores by gender&quot;,x=&quot;Gender&quot;, 
         y=&quot;SAT Verbal scores&quot;,fill=&quot;Gender&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Alternatively, use density plots to compare distributions</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;%
  ggplot(aes(x = SATV, fill = gender)) +
    geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;) +
    labs(title = &quot;Density plots of SAT Verbal scores by gender&quot;, 
         x = &quot;SAT Verbal scores&quot;, fill = &quot;Gender&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run a two sample t-test</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m3 &lt;- t.test(SATV ~ gender, var.eq = TRUE, data = scores)
m3</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  SATV by gender
## t = 0.49792, df = 698, p-value = 0.6187
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -13.09357  21.99137
## sample estimates:
##   mean in group Men mean in group Women 
##            615.1134            610.6645</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>report(m3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Effect sizes were labelled following Cohen&#39;s (1988) recommendations.
## 
## The Two Sample t-test testing the difference of SATV by gender (mean in group Men = 615.11, mean in group Women = 610.66) suggests that the effect is negative, statistically not significant, and very small (difference = -4.45, 95% CI [-13.09, 21.99], t(698) = 0.50, p = 0.619; Cohen&#39;s d = 0.04, 95% CI [-0.11, 0.19])</code></pre>
<p>t(df=698) = 0.49792, p-value = 61.87% &gt; 5% (fail to reject the null) -&gt; There is no statistically significant difference in average SAT verbal scores between men and women.</p>
</div>
<div id="one-way-anova" class="section level2">
<h2>One-way ANOVA</h2>
<p>It is used to determine whether there are group differences in numeric data between two or more groups.</p>
<p>Question: Do SAT verbal scores significantly differ by educational levels (1= HS, 2= some college degree, 3 = 2-year college degree, 4= 4-year college degree, 5= graduate work, 6=professional degree)?</p>
<p>Use boxplots to compare distributions of one quantitative variable across multiple categories; comparing distribution of <code>SATV</code> scores variable by education level</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;%
  ggplot(aes(x = education, y = SATV, fill = education)) +
    geom_boxplot(outlier.size = 1) +
    labs(title = &quot;Boxplots of SAT Verbal scores by education level&quot;,
         x = &quot;Levels of education&quot;, y = &quot;SAT Verbal scores&quot;, fill = &quot;Education&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run one-way ANOVA</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m4 &lt;- aov(SATV ~ education, data = scores)
summary(m4)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##              Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(&gt;F)
## education     5   80754   16151   1.269  0.275
## Residuals   694 8829392   12722</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>report(m4)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## For one-way between subjects designs, partial eta squared is equivalent to eta squared.
## Returning eta squared.</code></pre>
<pre><code>## The ANOVA (formula: SATV ~ education) suggests that:
## 
##   - The main effect of education is statistically not significant and very small (F(5, 694) = 1.27, p = 0.275; Eta2 = 9.06e-03, 90% CI [0.00, 0.02])
## 
## Effect sizes were labelled following Field&#39;s (2013) recommendations.</code></pre>
<p>F value(df Model=5, df Residuals=694) = 1.269, p-value = 27.5% &gt; 5% (fail to reject the null) -&gt; There were no significant group differences in SAT verbal scores according to students educational levels.</p>
<p>We do not have to run the post hoc tests because the group differences are not significant.</p>
<p>Tukeys HSD is the most popular post hoc test for comparing multiple pairings</p>
<pre class="r"><code>Tukey_ANOVA_SATV_ed &lt;- TukeyHSD(aov(SATV ~ education, data = scores), conf.level = .95) 
Tukey_ANOVA_SATV_ed</code></pre>
<pre><code>##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = SATV ~ education, data = scores)
## 
## $education
##            diff        lwr       upr     p adj
## 1-0 -16.8421053  -81.11952  47.43531 0.9756332
## 2-0 -40.4860447 -105.17035  24.19826 0.4737629
## 3-0  -4.3742265  -51.28442  42.53597 0.9998182
## 4-0   0.4405034  -50.31023  51.19124 1.0000000
## 5-0   4.8883912  -45.70428  55.48106 0.9997835
## 2-1 -23.6439394  -91.98228  44.69440 0.9215425
## 3-1  12.4678788  -39.36489  64.30064 0.9833397
## 4-1  17.2826087  -38.05008  72.61529 0.9482786
## 5-1  21.7304965  -33.45725  76.91824 0.8708907
## 3-2  36.1118182  -16.22468  88.44832 0.3596722
## 4-2  40.9265481  -14.87828  96.73138 0.2906084
## 5-2  45.3744358  -10.28669 101.03556 0.1835826
## 4-3   4.8147299  -28.81095  38.44041 0.9985288
## 5-3   9.2626177  -24.12403  42.64926 0.9687311
## 5-4   4.4478878  -34.14924  43.04502 0.9994867</code></pre>
<p>Optional: Some other commonly used post hoc tests are Bonferroni (more conservative) and Holm (less restrictive). Use <code>pairwise.t.test</code> for pairwise comparisons and indicate the adjustment method, e.g.<code>p.adj = &quot;holm&quot;</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>pairwise.t.test(scores$SATV, scores$education, p.adj=&quot;holm&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using t tests with pooled SD 
## 
## data:  scores$SATV and scores$education 
## 
##   0    1    2    3    4   
## 1 1.00 -    -    -    -   
## 2 0.89 1.00 -    -    -   
## 3 1.00 1.00 0.64 -    -   
## 4 1.00 1.00 0.51 1.00 -   
## 5 1.00 1.00 0.30 1.00 1.00
## 
## P value adjustment method: holm</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="two-way-anova" class="section level2">
<h2>Two-way ANOVA</h2>
<p>It is used to determine whether there are group differences in numeric data between groups characterized by two different categorical variables.</p>
<p>Question: Do SAT verbal scores significantly differ by educational levels and gender?</p>
<p>Use box plots to compare distribution of <code>SATV</code> scores variable by education level and gender (grouped by education level first, gender second)</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;%
  ggplot(aes(x = education, y = SATV, fill = gender)) +
    geom_boxplot(outlier.size = 1) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;) +
    labs(title = &quot;Boxplots of SAT Verbal scores by education level and gender&quot;,
         x = &quot;Level of education&quot;, y = &quot;SAT Verbal score&quot;, fill = &quot;Gender&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run two-way ANOVA</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m5 &lt;- aov(SATV ~ education + gender, data = scores)

summary(m5)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##              Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(&gt;F)
## education     5   80754   16151   1.269  0.276
## gender        1    6740    6740   0.529  0.467
## Residuals   693 8822652   12731</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>report(m5)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## The ANOVA (formula: SATV ~ education + gender) suggests that:
## 
##   - The main effect of education is statistically not significant and very small (F(5, 693) = 1.27, p = 0.276; Eta2 (partial) = 9.07e-03, 90% CI [0.00, 0.02])
##   - The main effect of gender is statistically not significant and very small (F(1, 693) = 0.53, p = 0.467; Eta2 (partial) = 7.63e-04, 90% CI [0.00, 7.99e-03])
## 
## Effect sizes were labelled following Field&#39;s (2013) recommendations.</code></pre>
<ul>
<li>Education: F value(df Model=5, df Residuals=693) = 1.269, p-value = 27.6% &gt; 5% (fail to reject the null)</li>
<li>Gender: F value(df Model=1, df Residuals=693) = 0.529, p-value = 46.7% &gt; 5% (fail to reject the null)</li>
</ul>
<p>There are no significant group differences in SAT verbal scores according to students educational levels or gender.</p>
</div>
<div id="chi-square-test-of-independence" class="section level2">
<h2>Chi-square test of independence</h2>
<p>It is used to determine whether two categorical variables are dependent or independent.</p>
<p>Question: Is gender independent of education levels?</p>
<p>Make a bar-chart showing distribution of observations by gender and education</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;% 
  ggplot(aes(fill = gender, x = education)) + 
    geom_bar(position = &quot;fill&quot;) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;) +
    geom_text(aes(y = ..count../tapply(..count.., ..x.. ,sum)[..x..], 
                  label = scales::percent(..count../tapply(..count.., ..x.. ,sum)[..x..]) ),
                  stat = &quot;count&quot;, position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +  
    labs(title = &quot;Distribution of observations by gender and education levels&quot;,
         x = &quot;Education levels&quot;, y = &quot;Number of observations&quot;, fill = &quot;Gender&quot;) +
    coord_flip()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run a Chi-square test of independence</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m6 &lt;- chisq.test(table(scores$gender, scores$education))
m6</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  Pearson&#39;s Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(scores$gender, scores$education)
## X-squared = 16.085, df = 5, p-value = 0.006605</code></pre>
<p>X-squared(df=5) = 16.085, p-value = 0.006% &lt; 5% (reject the null) -&gt; Gender and education levels are dependent.</p>
</div>
<div id="simple-linear-regression" class="section level2">
<h2>Simple linear regression</h2>
<p>It is used to identify a presence of a linear relationship between two quantitative variables.</p>
<p>Question: Is there a linear relationship between SAT Verbal and SAT Quantitative scores?</p>
<p>Make a scatter plot with a best-fit line</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(scores, aes(x = SATQ, y = SATV)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  labs(title = &quot;Scatteplot of SAT Verbal and SAT Quantitative scores&quot;,
       x = &quot;SAT Quantitative score&quot;, y = &quot;SAT Verbal score&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## `geom_smooth()` using formula &#39;y ~ x&#39;</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run a simple linear regression</p>
<pre class="r"><code>model1 &lt;- lm(SATV ~ SATQ, data = scores)
summary(model1)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SATV ~ SATQ, data = scores)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -365.89  -50.57   -3.23   54.68  257.74 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(&gt;|t|)    
## (Intercept) 227.14322   17.77978   12.78   &lt;2e-16 ***
## SATQ          0.63124    0.02863   22.05   &lt;2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 86.71 on 685 degrees of freedom
##   (13 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4151, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4143 
## F-statistic: 486.2 on 1 and 685 DF,  p-value: &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<p>T-test for Beta1:</p>
<ul>
<li>t-stat(SATQ) = 22.05, p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null)</li>
<li>There is a linear relationship between SAT Quantitative scores and SAT Verbal scores.</li>
</ul>
<p>ANOVA for Regression:</p>
<ul>
<li>F-stat(1,685) = 486.2, p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null)</li>
<li>The overall model is worthwhile.</li>
</ul>
<p>Overall:</p>
<ul>
<li>The estimated regression line equation: SATV = 227.14 + 0.63(SATQ). We would expect 0.63 points increase in SAT Verbal scores for every one point increase in SAT Quantitative score, assuming all the other variables are held constant.</li>
<li>41.51% of the variability in the SAT verbal scores was explained by the SAT quantitative scores.</li>
</ul>
<p>Get a formal report for the model</p>
<pre class="r"><code>report(model1)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict SATV with SATQ (formula: SATV ~ SATQ). The model explains a statistically significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2 = 0.42, F(1, 685) = 486.19, p &lt; .001, adj. R2 = 0.41). The model&#39;s intercept, corresponding to SATQ = 0, is at 227.14 (95% CI [192.23, 262.05], t(685) = 12.78, p &lt; .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of SATQ is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.63, 95% CI [0.58, 0.69], t(685) = 22.05, p &lt; .001; Std. beta = 0.64, 95% CI [0.59, 0.70])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset.</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="multiple-linear-regression" class="section level2">
<h2>Multiple linear regression</h2>
<p>It is used to explain/predict one quantitative variable using multiple explanatory variables (one of which has to be quantitative).</p>
<p>Question: Can you explain/predict SAT Verbal using SAT Quantitative scores and ACT scores?</p>
<p>Make a correlation matrix</p>
<pre class="r"><code>scores %&gt;%
  select(SATV, SATQ, ACT) %&gt;% 
  ggpairs(aes())</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Run a multiple linear regression</p>
<pre class="r"><code>model2 &lt;- lm(SATV ~ SATQ + ACT, data = scores)
summary(model2)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SATV ~ SATQ + ACT, data = scores)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -376.97  -46.64    1.89   50.25  243.20 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(&gt;|t|)    
## (Intercept) 138.57027   20.25101   6.843 1.73e-11 ***
## SATQ          0.47130    0.03382  13.934  &lt; 2e-16 ***
## ACT           6.52075    0.80963   8.054 3.56e-15 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 82.93 on 684 degrees of freedom
##   (13 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4658, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4642 
## F-statistic: 298.2 on 2 and 684 DF,  p-value: &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<p>Get a formal report for the model</p>
<pre class="r"><code>report(model2)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict SATV with SATQ and ACT (formula: SATV ~ SATQ + ACT). The model explains a statistically significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2 = 0.47, F(2, 684) = 298.19, p &lt; .001, adj. R2 = 0.46). The model&#39;s intercept, corresponding to SATQ = 0 and ACT = 0, is at 138.57 (95% CI [98.81, 178.33], t(684) = 6.84, p &lt; .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of SATQ is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.47, 95% CI [0.40, 0.54], t(684) = 13.93, p &lt; .001; Std. beta = 0.48, 95% CI [0.41, 0.55])
##   - The effect of ACT is statistically significant and positive (beta = 6.52, 95% CI [4.93, 8.11], t(684) = 8.05, p &lt; .001; Std. beta = 0.28, 95% CI [0.21, 0.35])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset.</code></pre>
<div id="multicollinearity" class="section level3">
<h3>Multicollinearity</h3>
<p>Multicollinearity may occur when an independent variable is highly correlated (r &gt;= 0.7) with one or more of the other independent variables in the model.</p>
<p>What if we wanted to add more predictors to the model?</p>
<pre class="r"><code># transform education variable to be numeric
scores$education &lt;- as.numeric(scores$education)

scores %&gt;%
  ggpairs(aes(fill = gender, color = gender, alpha = 0.3), progress = F) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = &quot;Dark2&quot;)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>model3 &lt;- lm(SATV ~ SATQ + ACT + age + education + gender, data = scores)
summary(model3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SATV ~ SATQ + ACT + age + education + gender, data = scores)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -386.97  -43.23    2.44   51.91  240.16 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(&gt;|t|)    
## (Intercept) 136.25377   22.59310   6.031 2.68e-09 ***
## SATQ          0.47786    0.03445  13.873  &lt; 2e-16 ***
## ACT           6.61477    0.82185   8.049 3.73e-15 ***
## age          -0.74316    0.40359  -1.841   0.0660 .  
## education     0.96598    2.70177   0.358   0.7208    
## genderWomen  16.56045    6.73492   2.459   0.0142 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 82.46 on 681 degrees of freedom
##   (13 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4741, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4703 
## F-statistic: 122.8 on 5 and 681 DF,  p-value: &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<p>T-tests for Beta1:</p>
<ul>
<li>SATQ: p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null) -&gt; There is a statistically significant linear relationship between SATQ and SATV scores.</li>
<li>ACT: p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null) -&gt; There is a statistically significant linear relationship between ACT and SATV scores.</li>
<li>Age: p-value = 6.60% &gt; 5% (fail to reject the null) -&gt; A linear relationship between age and SATV scores is not statistically significant.</li>
<li>Education: p-value = 72.08% &gt; 5% (fail to reject the null) -&gt; A linear relationship between education and SATV scores is not statistically significant.</li>
<li>Gender: p-value = 1.42% &lt; 5 % (reject the null) -&gt; There is a statistically significant linear relationship between gender and SATV scores.</li>
</ul>
<p>ANOVA for Regression: - F-stat(5,681) = 122.8, p-value = 0.00% &lt; 5% (reject the null) - The overall model is worthwhile.</p>
<p>Overall: - The estimated regression line equation: SATV = 136.25 + 0.48(SATQ) + 6.61(ACT) - 0.74(Age) + 0.97(Education) + 16.56(GenderWomen). - 47.41% of the variability in the SAT verbal scores was explained by the model as a whole.</p>
<p>Get a formal report on your model</p>
<pre class="r"><code>report(model3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict SATV with SATQ, ACT, age, education and gender (formula: SATV ~ SATQ + ACT + age + education + gender). The model explains a statistically significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2 = 0.47, F(5, 681) = 122.80, p &lt; .001, adj. R2 = 0.47). The model&#39;s intercept, corresponding to SATQ = 0, ACT = 0, age = 0, education = 0 and gender = Men, is at 136.25 (95% CI [91.89, 180.61], t(681) = 6.03, p &lt; .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of SATQ is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.48, 95% CI [0.41, 0.55], t(681) = 13.87, p &lt; .001; Std. beta = 0.49, 95% CI [0.42, 0.56])
##   - The effect of ACT is statistically significant and positive (beta = 6.61, 95% CI [5.00, 8.23], t(681) = 8.05, p &lt; .001; Std. beta = 0.28, 95% CI [0.21, 0.35])
##   - The effect of age is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.74, 95% CI [-1.54, 0.05], t(681) = -1.84, p = 0.066; Std. beta = -0.06, 95% CI [-0.13, 4.13e-03])
##   - The effect of education is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.97, 95% CI [-4.34, 6.27], t(681) = 0.36, p = 0.721; Std. beta = 0.01, 95% CI [-0.05, 0.08])
##   - The effect of gender [Women] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 16.56, 95% CI [3.34, 29.78], t(681) = 2.46, p = 0.014; Std. beta = 0.15, 95% CI [0.03, 0.26])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset.</code></pre>
<p>Check Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) for the severity of multicollinearity</p>
<pre class="r"><code>vif(model3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      SATQ       ACT       age education    gender 
##  1.600706  1.590366  1.479992  1.494064  1.051513</code></pre>
<p>VIF values above 4 - moderate multicollinearity; above 10 - strong multicollinearity</p>
</div>
<div id="f-test-for-nested-models" class="section level3">
<h3>F-test for nested models</h3>
<p>Run F-test for comparing nested models</p>
<pre class="r"><code>anova(model1, model2, model3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: SATV ~ SATQ
## Model 2: SATV ~ SATQ + ACT
## Model 3: SATV ~ SATQ + ACT + age + education + gender
##   Res.Df     RSS Df Sum of Sq      F    Pr(&gt;F)    
## 1    685 5150020                                  
## 2    684 4703926  1    446094 65.606 2.546e-15 ***
## 3    681 4630511  3     73415  3.599   0.01334 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1</code></pre>
<p>P-values below 5% indicate that the new model is an improvement over the previous one:</p>
<ul>
<li>Model 2 is an improvement over Model 1 (coefficient for ACT is not a zero)</li>
<li>Model 3 is an improvement over Model 2 (coefficient for Gender is not a zero)</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="assumptions-of-linear-regression" class="section level2">
<h2>Assumptions of linear regression</h2>
<ul>
<li>Normality of residuals: residual errors are assumed to be normally distributed.</li>
<li>Homoscedasticity of residuals variance: residuals are assumed to have a constant variance</li>
<li>Independence of residual error terms: residuals should be independent of each other.</li>
<li>Linearity: the relationship between predictors and outcome variable is assumed to be linear.</li>
</ul>
<div id="normality" class="section level3">
<h3>Normality</h3>
<p>Normal Q-Q plot</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot=plot(model3, 2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Checking for normality using Shapiro-Wilk test:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>shapiro.test(resid(model3))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(model3)
## W = 0.98587, p-value = 3.383e-06</code></pre>
<p>p-values below 5% indicate non-normality of residuals</p>
</div>
<div id="homoscedasticity" class="section level3">
<h3>Homoscedasticity</h3>
<p>Plot positive values of residuals against fitted values</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot=plot(model3, 3)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Checking for heteroscedasticity using Breusch-Pagan Test</p>
<pre class="r"><code>bptest(model3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  model3
## BP = 23.592, df = 5, p-value = 0.00026</code></pre>
<p>p-values below 5% indicate heteroscedasticity of residuals</p>
</div>
<div id="independence-and-linearity" class="section level3">
<h3>Independence and linearity</h3>
<p>Residuals vs Fitted plot to check if the observed pattern is linear</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot=plot(model3, 1)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Checking for auto-correlation using Durbin-Watson Test.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>durbinWatsonTest(model3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1      -0.1095882      2.218698   0.002
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0</code></pre>
<p>For the independent data, DW statistic is close to 2. DW &lt; 1 or DW &gt; 3 may indicate the presence of autocorrelation.</p>
<p>p-values below 5% indicate autocorrelation of residuals.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="forest-plots" class="section level2">
<h2>Forest plots</h2>
<p>Forest plot enables you to visualize regression coefficients with CIs (uses <code>sjplot</code> package)</p>

            m.labels = c(&quot;Model 1&quot;,&quot;Model 2&quot;,&quot;Model 3&quot;),
            legend.title = &quot;Models&quot;,
            show.values = TRUE,
            vline.color = &quot;black&quot;)</code></pre>

</div>

<div id="optional" class="section level1">
<h1>Optional</h1>
<div id="simple-logistic-regression" class="section level2">
<h2>Simple logistic regression</h2>
<p>It is used to explain/predict one binary variable using one quantitative independent variables.</p>
<p>Question: Can you predict ones gender using ones SAT Quantitative score?</p>
<p>Run a simple logistic regression</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m7 &lt;- glm(gender ~ SATQ, family = binomial, data = scores)
summary(m7)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = gender ~ SATQ, family = binomial, data = scores)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.8857  -1.3047   0.8054   0.9798   1.1734  
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(&gt;|z|)    
## (Intercept)  2.5427964  0.4686452   5.426 5.77e-08 ***
## SATQ        -0.0031667  0.0007407  -4.275 1.91e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 895.09  on 686  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 875.67  on 685  degrees of freedom
##   (13 observations deleted due to missingness)
## AIC: 879.67
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>report(m7)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## We fitted a logistic model (estimated using ML) to predict gender with SATQ (formula: gender ~ SATQ). The model&#39;s explanatory power is weak (Tjur&#39;s R2 = 0.03). The model&#39;s intercept, corresponding to SATQ = 0, is at 2.54 (95% CI [1.64, 3.48], p &lt; .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of SATQ is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.17e-03, 95% CI [-4.64e-03, -1.74e-03], p &lt; .001; Std. beta = -0.37, 95% CI [-0.54, -0.20])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="multiple-logistic-regression" class="section level2">
<h2>Multiple logistic regression</h2>
<p>It is used to explain/predict one binary variable using multiple explanatory variables (one of which has to be quantitative).</p>
<p>Question: Can you predict ones gender using ones SAT Quantitative and Verbal scores?</p>
<p>Run a multiple logistic regression</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m8 &lt;- glm(gender ~ SATQ + SATV, family = binomial, data = scores)
summary(m8)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = gender ~ SATQ + SATV, family = binomial, data = scores)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -2.0323  -1.2901   0.7977   0.9594   1.4946  
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(&gt;|z|)    
## (Intercept)  1.9120390  0.5066135   3.774 0.000161 ***
## SATQ        -0.0050271  0.0009834  -5.112 3.19e-07 ***
## SATV         0.0028975  0.0009699   2.987 0.002814 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 895.09  on 686  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 866.51  on 684  degrees of freedom
##   (13 observations deleted due to missingness)
## AIC: 872.51
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>report(m8)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## We fitted a logistic model (estimated using ML) to predict gender with SATQ and SATV (formula: gender ~ SATQ + SATV). The model&#39;s explanatory power is weak (Tjur&#39;s R2 = 0.04). The model&#39;s intercept, corresponding to SATQ = 0 and SATV = 0, is at 1.91 (95% CI [0.93, 2.92], p &lt; .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of SATQ is statistically significant and negative (beta = -5.03e-03, 95% CI [-6.99e-03, -3.13e-03], p &lt; .001; Std. beta = -0.58, 95% CI [-0.81, -0.36])
##   - The effect of SATV is statistically significant and positive (beta = 2.90e-03, 95% CI [1.01e-03, 4.82e-03], p = 0.003; Std. beta = 0.33, 95% CI [0.11, 0.55])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using</code></pre>
</div>
